# Tailscale File Transfer Lab - Phone to Ginger

Date: 2026-05-10  
Lab Type: Remote Access / File Transfer / Tailscale  
Status: Successful  

## Overview

In this lab, I tested transferring a file from my phone to my Kali Linux VM named 'ginger' using Tailscale file transfer.

At first, I could not find the test files I had sent earlier. I suspect that there is a time limit for transfers to be completed, but I do not know that for sure. 
Since they were not important, I created a dedicated folder on Ginger so future Tailscale transfers have a known landing location.

## Lab Goal
Create a clean directory on Ginger for Tailscale file transfers and successfully retrieve a file sent from my phone.

## Systems Used

| System | Role |
|---|---|
| Phone | File sender |
| Ginger | Kali Linux VM receiving the file |
| Tailscale | Private mesh VPN / file transfer tool |

## Steps Completed
1. Created a Tailscale transfer directory
On Ginger, I created a dedicated folder for Tailscale file transfers.

mkdir -p ~/transfers/tailscale

After sending a student_handbook.pdf from my phone through the Tailscale app, I retrieved it on ginger with:

sudo tailscale file get ~/transfers/tailscale

That tells Tailscale: Take the waiting file transfer and save it into this folder. You do NOT need the filename to do this.

## What I Learned
Tailscale can transfer files from my phone to a Linux system in my tailnet.
tailscale file get is used on the receiving machine to download pending files.
Creating a dedicated transfer directory makes file management much cleaner.
The dquote> prompt means the shell is waiting for a closing double quote.
Using sudo may cause downloaded files to be owned by root, so ownership should be checked after the transfer.

